# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secrets-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] A **hardware security module** (**HSM**) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages secrets (most importantly digital keys), and performs encryption and decryption functions for digital signatures, strong authentication and other cryptographic functions.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] HSMs may have features that provide tamper evidence such as visible signs of tampering or logging and alerting, or tamper resistance which makes tampering difficult without making the HSM inoperable, or tamper responsiveness such as deleting keys upon tamper detection.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Each module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips to prevent tampering and bus probing, or a combination of chips in a module that is protected by the tamper evident, tamper resistant, or tamper responsive packaging.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] A vast majority of existing HSMs are designed mainly to manage secret keys.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Many HSM systems have means to securely back up the keys they handle outside of the HSM.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Keys may be backed up in wrapped form and stored on a computer disk or other media, or externally using a secure portable device like a smartcard or some other security token.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] HSMs are used for real time authorization and authentication in critical infrastructure thus are typically engineered to support standard high availability models including clustering, automated failover, and redundant field-replaceable components.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] A few of the HSMs available in the market have the capability to execute specially developed modules within the HSM's secure enclosure.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Such an ability is useful, for example, in cases where special algorithms or business logic has to be executed in a secured and controlled environment.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] The modules can be developed in native C language, .NET, Java, or other programming languages.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Although the highest level of FIPS 140 security certification attainable is Security Level 4, most of the HSMs have Level 3 certification.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] In the Common Criteria system the highest EAL (Evaluation Assurance Level) is EAL7; most of the HSMs have EAL4+ certification.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] When used in financial payments applications, the security of an HSM is often validated against the HSM requirements defined by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module can be employed in any application that uses digital keys.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Typically, the keys would be of high value - meaning there would be a significant, negative impact to the owner of the key if it were compromised.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] HSMs are also deployed to manage transparent data encryption keys for databases and keys for storage devices such as disk or tape.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Some HSM systems are also hardware cryptographic accelerators.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] They usually cannot beat the performance of hardware-only solutions for symmetric key operations.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] However, with performance ranges from 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA signatures per second, HSMs can provide significant CPU offload for asymmetric key operations.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Since the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is recommending the use of 2,048 bit RSA keys from year 2010, performance at longer key sizes has become more important.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] To address this issue, most HSMs now support elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which delivers stronger encryption with shorter key lengths.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] In PKI environments, the HSMs may be used by certification authorities (CAs) and registration authorities (RAs) to generate, store, and handle asymmetric key pairs.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] On the other hand, device performance in a PKI environment is generally less important, in both online and offline operations, as Registration Authority procedures represent the performance bottleneck of the Infrastructure.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Specialized HSMs are used in the payment card industry.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] HSMs support both general-purpose functions and specialized functions required to process transactions and comply with industry standards.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] They normally do not feature a standard API.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] The major organizations that produce and maintain standards for HSMs on the banking market are the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, ANS X9, and ISO.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Performance-critical applications that have to use HTTPS (SSL/TLS), can benefit from the use of an SSL Acceleration HSM by moving the RSA operations, which typically requires several large integer multiplications, from the host CPU to the HSM device.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Typical HSM devices can perform about 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA operations/second.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Some performance at longer key sizes is becoming increasingly important.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] An increasing number of registries use HSMs to store the key material that is used to sign large zonefiles.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] OpenDNSSEC is an open-source tool that manages signing DNS zone files.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] On January 27, 2007, ICANN and Verisign, with support from the U.S.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Department of Commerce, started deploying DNSSEC for DNS root zones.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Root signature details can be found on the Root DNSSEC's website.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Blockchain technology depends on cryptographic operations.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Safeguarding private keys is essential to maintain the security of blockchain processes that utilize asymmetric cryptography.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] The private keys are often stored in a cryptocurrency wallet like the hardware wallet in the image.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] The synergy between HSMs and blockchain is mentioned in several papers, emphasizing their role in securing private keys and verifying identity, e.g. in contexts such as blockchain-driven mobility solutions.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Automotive hardware security modules (HSMs) are embedded cryptographic coprocessors integrated into electronic control units (ECUs) to protect in-vehicle systems and communication buses against manipulation and misuse.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] They act as a hardware root of trust by securely generating and storing cryptographic keys and offloading security-critical operations such as secure boot, encryption, decryption, authentication and attestation.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] In modern ECU designs, HSMs are one of several hardware primitives that can underpin a hardware root of trust alongside secure elements, trusted platform modules (TPMs), one-time programmable (OTP) and read-only memories (ROM), and physical unclonable functions (PUFs).
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Their use provides dedicated hardware support for cryptographic operations, but also introduces trade-offs in die area, power consumption and latency, so they are typically integrated into mid- and high-end automotive domain controllers rather than the smallest microcontrollers.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Automotive HSMs are typically accompanied by dedicated firmware and software components that manage access to cryptographic services.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] These include HSM firmware, secure boot loaders, cryptographic libraries, and middleware that expose security services to the operating system and application software.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] In AUTOSAR-based systems, HSM firmware may interface with standardized service layers to provide cryptographic operations to applications.
[src:secrets-management/hardware-security-module] Commercial HSM firmware implementations are available from several automotive software vendors, often as components integrated into AUTOSAR platforms or OEM security frameworks.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:secrets-management/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:secrets-management/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] A **password manager** is a software program that prevents password fatigue by automatically generating, autofilling, and storing passwords.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] They are useful for local applications or web applications such as online shops or social media.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Web browsers tend to have a built-in password manager.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Password managers typically require a user to create and remember a single master password to unlock the database and access the stored passwords.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Password managers can integrate multi-factor authentication and passkey authentication.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] The first password manager software designed to securely store passwords was Password Safe created by Bruce Schneier, which was released as a free utility on September 5, 1997.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Designed for Microsoft Windows 95, Password Safe used Schneier's Blowfish algorithm to encrypt passwords and other sensitive data.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Although Password Safe was released as a free utility, due to export restrictions on cryptography from the United States, only U.S. and Canadian citizens and permanent residents were initially allowed to download it.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Several other browser-based password managers were launched in the late 1990s including RoboForm (1999) developed by Siber Systems and Obongo (1999), a Sequoia Capital backed company, later acquired by America Online in 2001.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] As of October 2024, the built-in Google Password Manager in Google Chrome has become the most used password manager.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] These are built directly into web browsers like Chrome, Safari, Firefox, and Edge.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] They offer convenient access for basic password management on the device where the browser is used.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] These are standalone applications installed on a user's device.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] They offer strong security as passwords are stored locally, but access may be limited to that specific device.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] These store passwords in encrypted form on remote servers, allowing access from supported internet-connected devices.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] They typically offer features like automatic syncing, secure sharing, and strong encryption.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Designed for businesses, these cater to managing access credentials within an organization.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] They integrate with existing directory services and access control systems, often offering advanced features like role-based permissions and privileged access management.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] These physical devices, often USB keys, provide an extra layer of security for password management.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Others also offer offline storage for passwords, such as OnlyKey and Nitrokey.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some applications store passwords as an unencrypted file, leaving the passwords easily accessible to malware or people attempting to steal personal information.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some password managers require a user-selected master password to derive the key used to encrypt passwords stored for the application to read.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] The security of this approach depends on the strength of the chosen master password (which may be brute-forced by an attacker), and also that the master password itself is never stored locally where a malicious program or individual could read it.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] A compromised master password may render all of the encrypted passwords vulnerable, meaning that a single point of entry can compromise the confidentiality of sensitive information.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] This is known as a single point of failure.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] While password managers offer robust security for credentials, their effectiveness hinges on the user's device security.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] If a device is compromised by malware like Raccoon, which excels at stealing data, the password manager's protections can be nullified.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Malware like keyloggers can steal the master password used to access the password manager, granting full access to all stored credentials.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Clipboard sniffers can capture sensitive information copied from the manager, and some malware might even steal the encrypted password vault file itself.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] In essence, a compromised device with password-stealing malware can bypass the security measures of the password manager, leaving the stored credentials vulnerable.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] As with password authentication techniques, key logging or acoustic cryptanalysis may be used to guess or copy the "master password".
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some password managers attempt to use virtual keyboards to reduce this risk - though this is still vulnerable to key loggers that take the keystrokes and send what key was pressed to the person/people trying to access confidential information.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Cloud-based password managers offer a centralized location for storing login credentials.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] However, this approach raises security concerns.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] One potential vulnerability is a data breach at the password manager itself.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] If such an event were to occur, attackers could potentially gain access to a large number of user credentials.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] A 2022 security incident involving LastPass exemplifies this risk.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some password managers may include a password generator.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Generated passwords may be guessable if the password manager uses a weak method of randomly generating a "seed" for all passwords generated by this program.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] There are documented cases, like the one with Kaspersky Password Manager in 2021, where a flaw in the password generation method resulted in predictable passwords.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] A 2014 paper by researchers at Carnegie Mellon University found that while browsers refuse to autofill passwords if the login page protocol differs from when the password was saved (HTTP vs.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] HTTPS), some password managers insecurely filled passwords for the unencrypted (HTTP) version of saved passwords for encrypted (HTTPS) sites.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Additionally, most managers lacked protection against iframe and redirection-based attacks, potentially exposing additional passwords when password synchronization was used across multiple devices.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] A 2026 paper by researchers at ETH Zurich analyzed four popular commercial password managers and found 27 attacks in 4 attack categories.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some vulnerabilities were present because vulnerable cryptographic algorithms were still present due to backward compatibility.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Others were possible because items were individually encrypted which allows field swapping, metadata leakage and downgrade attacks.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Some attacks were possible because of unauthenticated public keys allowing a malicious server to replace keys.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] While most vulnerabilities have been fixed, vendors responded that public key authentication is out of scope.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Various high-profile websites and client-security products have attempted to block or discourage the use of password managers.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Techniques have included disabling password autofill, preventing users from pasting into password fields, or setting `autocomplete="off"` on login forms.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] In 2015, British Gas blocked password managers before reversing the change following public criticism.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Other reported examples included T-Mobile, Barclaycard, and Western Union restricting password pasting, often citing concerns such as malware, phishing, or automated attacks.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] The Trusteer client security software from IBM has included explicit options to block password managers.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Such blocking has been criticized by information security professionals as making users less secure, because it can discourage the use of strong, unique, machine-generated passwords.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Research presented at the 2014 USENIX Security Symposium also described websites using form attributes and scripts to interfere with password managers.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] Modern browser behavior and security guidance have moved toward accommodating password managers.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] MDN Web Docs notes that many modern browsers do not support `autocomplete="off"` for login fields and may still offer to save and autofill credentials.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] *NIST Special Publication 800-63B* states that verifiers shall allow password managers and autofill functionality and should permit pasting passwords when autofill APIs are unavailable.
[src:secrets-management/password-manager] The OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet similarly recommends that web applications allow users to paste into username, password, and multi-factor authentication fields.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In one type of secret sharing scheme there is one *dealer* and *n* *players*.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The dealer gives a share of the secret to the players, but only when specific conditions are fulfilled will the players be able to reconstruct the secret from their shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The dealer accomplishes this by giving each player a share in such a way that any group of *t* (for *threshold*) or more players can together reconstruct the secret but no group of fewer than *t* players can.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Such a system is called a (*t*, *n*)-threshold scheme (sometimes it is written as an (*n*, *t*)-threshold scheme).
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing was invented independently by Adi Shamir and George Blakley in 1979.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are ideal for storing information that is highly sensitive and highly important.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Examples include: encryption keys, missile launch codes, and numbered bank accounts.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Each of these pieces of information must be kept highly confidential, as their exposure could be disastrous; however, it is also critical that they should not be lost.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Traditional methods for encryption are ill-suited for simultaneously achieving high levels of confidentiality and reliability.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This is because when storing the encryption key, one must choose between keeping a single copy of the key in one location for maximum secrecy, or keeping multiple copies of the key in different locations for greater reliability.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Increasing reliability of the key by storing multiple copies lowers confidentiality by creating additional attack vectors; there are more opportunities for a copy to fall into the wrong hands.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes address this problem, and allow arbitrarily high levels of confidentiality and reliability to be achieved.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing also allows the distributor of the secret to trust a group 'in aggregate'.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Traditionally, giving a secret to a group for safekeeping would require that the distributor completely trust all members of the group.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes allow the distributor to securely store the secret with the group even if not all members can be trusted all the time.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] So long as the number of traitors is never more than the critical number needed to reconstruct the secret, the secret is safe.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are important in cloud computing environments.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Thus a key can be distributed over many servers by a threshold secret sharing mechanism.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The key is then reconstructed when needed.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing has also been suggested for sensor networks where the links are liable to be tapped, by sending the data in shares which makes the task of the eavesdropper harder.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The security in such environments can be made greater by continuous changing of the way the shares are constructed.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A secure secret sharing scheme distributes shares so that anyone with fewer than *t* shares has no more information about the secret than someone with 0 shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Consider for example the secret sharing scheme in which the secret phrase "password" is divided into the shares "pa––––––", "––ss––––", "––––wo––", and "––––––rd".
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A person with 0 shares knows only that the password consists of eight letters, and thus would have to guess the password from 268 = 208 billion possible combinations.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A person with one share, however, would have to guess only the six letters, from 266 = 308 million combinations, and so on as more persons collude.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Consequently, this system is not a "secure" secret sharing scheme, because a player with fewer than *t* secret shares is able to reduce the problem of obtaining the inner secret without first needing to obtain all of the necessary shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In contrast, consider the secret sharing scheme where *X* is the secret to be shared, *Pi* are public asymmetric encryption keys and *Qi* their corresponding private keys.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any player with private key 1 can remove the outer layer of encryption, a player with keys 1 and 2 can remove the first and second layer, and so on.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A player with fewer than *N* keys can never fully reach the secret *X* without first needing to decrypt a public-key-encrypted blob for which he does not have the corresponding private key – a problem that is currently believed to be computationally infeasible.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Additionally we can see that any user with all *N* private keys is able to decrypt all of the outer layers to obtain *X*, the secret, and consequently this system is a secure secret distribution system.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Several secret-sharing schemes are said to be information-theoretically secure and can be proven to be so, while others give up this *unconditional security* for improved efficiency while maintaining enough security to be considered as secure as other common cryptographic primitives.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For example, they might allow secrets to be protected by shares with entropy of 128 bits each, since each share would be considered enough to stymie any conceivable present-day adversary, requiring a brute force attack of average size 2127.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Note: *n* is the total number of 'players', among whom the shares are distributed, and *t* is the minimum number of players required to reveal the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Instead, (1) can be performed using the binary operation in any group.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For example, take the cyclic group of integers with addition modulo 232, which corresponds to 32-bit integers with addition defined with the binary overflow being discarded.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The secret *s* can be partitioned into a vector of *M* 32-bit integers, which we call *v*secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Then (*n* − 1) of the players are each given a vector of *M* 32-bit integers that is drawn independently from a uniform probability distribution, with player *i* receiving *vi*.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The secret vector can then be recovered by summing across all the players' vectors.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The difficulty lies in creating schemes that are still secure, but do not require all *n* shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] When space efficiency is not a concern, trivial *t* = *n* schemes can be used to reveal a secret to any desired subsets of the players simply by applying the scheme for each subset.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For example, to reveal a secret *s* to any two of the three players Alice, Bob and Carol, create three ( ${\binom {3}{2}}$ ) different *t* = *n* = 2 secret shares for *s*, giving the three sets of two shares to Alice and Bob, Alice and Carol, and Bob and Carol.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For example, imagine that the board of directors of a company would like to protect their secret formula.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The president of the company should be able to access the formula when needed, but in an emergency any 3 of the 12 board members would be able to unlock the secret formula together.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] One of the ways this can be accomplished is by a secret-sharing scheme with *t* = 3 and *n* = 15, where 3 shares are given to the president, and one share is given to each board member.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In the worst case, the increase is exponential.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This has led to the search for schemes that allow secrets to be shared efficiently with a threshold of players.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A ramp secret sharing scheme is a secret-sharing scheme with two thresholds: groups below the lower threshold learn no information about the secret, groups at or above the upper threshold can reconstruct it, and intermediate-size groups may obtain partial information.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This relaxation can reduce the size of shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Hirosuke Yamamoto's (*k*, *L*, *n*) threshold scheme is an early information-theoretic formulation of this trade-off.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any *t* out of *n* shares may be used to recover the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The system relies on the idea that one can construct a unique polynomial of degree *t* − 1, such that each of the *t* points lies on the polynomial.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] It takes two points to define a straight line, three points to fully define a quadratic, four points to define a cubic curve, and so on.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] That is, it takes *t* points to define a polynomial of degree *t* − 1.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The method is to create a polynomial of degree *t* − 1 with the secret as the first coefficient and the remaining coefficients picked at random.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Next find *n* points on the curve and give one to each of the players.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] When at least *t* out of the *n* players reveal their points, there is sufficient information to fit a (*t* − 1)th degree polynomial to them, the first coefficient being the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] , and the secret is the point at which three shares intersect.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Two nonparallel lines in the same plane intersect at exactly one point.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Three nonparallel planes in space intersect at exactly one point.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] More generally, any *n* nonparallel (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes intersect at a specific point.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The secret may be encoded as any single coordinate of the point of intersection.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If the secret is encoded using all the coordinates, even if they are random, then an insider (someone in possession of one or more of the (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes) gains information about the secret since he knows it must lie on his plane.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If an insider can gain any more knowledge about the secret than an outsider can, then the system no longer has information theoretic security.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If only one of the *n* coordinates is used, then the insider knows no more than an outsider (i.e., that the secret must lie on the *x*-axis for a 2-dimensional system).
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Each player is given enough information to define a hyperplane; the secret is recovered by calculating the planes' point of intersection and then taking a specified coordinate of that intersection.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme is less space-efficient than Shamir's; while Shamir's shares are each only as large as the original secret, Blakley's shares are *t* times larger, where *t* is the threshold number of players.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme can be tightened by adding restrictions on which planes are usable as shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The resulting scheme is equivalent to Shamir's polynomial system.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The Chinese remainder theorem can also be used in secret sharing, for it provides us with a method to uniquely determine a number *S* modulo *k* many pairwise coprime integers $m_{1},m_{2},...,m_{k}$ , given that $S<\prod _{i=1}^{k}m_{i}$ .
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] There are two secret sharing schemes that make use of the Chinese remainder theorem, Mignotte's and Asmuth-Bloom's Schemes.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] They are threshold secret sharing schemes, in which the shares are generated by reduction modulo the integers $m_{i}$ , and the secret is recovered by essentially solving the system of congruences using the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If the players store their shares on insecure computer servers, an attacker could crack in and steal the shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If it is not practical to change the secret, the uncompromised (Shamir-style) shares can be renewed.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The dealer generates a new random polynomial with constant term zero and calculates for each remaining player a new ordered pair, where the x-coordinates of the old and new pairs are the same.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Each player then adds the old and new y-coordinates to each other and keeps the result as the new y-coordinate of the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] All of the non-updated shares the attacker accumulated become useless.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] An attacker can only recover the secret if he can find enough other non-updated shares to reach the threshold.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This situation should not happen because the players deleted their old shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Additionally, an attacker cannot recover any information about the original secret from the update files because they contain only random information.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The dealer can change the threshold number while distributing updates, but must always remain vigilant of players keeping expired shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A player might lie about his own share to gain access to other shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A *verifiable secret sharing* (VSS) scheme allows players to be certain that no other players are lying about the contents of their shares, up to a reasonable probability of error.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Such schemes cannot be computed conventionally; the players must collectively add and multiply numbers without any individual's knowing what exactly is being added and multiplied.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The disadvantage of unconditionally secure secret sharing schemes is that the storage and transmission of the shares requires an amount of storage and bandwidth resources equivalent to the size of the secret times the number of shares.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] If the size of the secret were significant, say 1 GB, and the number of shares were 10, then 10 GB of data must be stored by the shareholders.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Alternate techniques have been proposed for greatly increasing the efficiency of secret sharing schemes, by giving up the requirement of unconditional security.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] One of these techniques, known as *secret sharing made short*, combines Rabin's information dispersal algorithm (IDA) with Shamir's secret sharing.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Data is first encrypted with a randomly generated key, using a symmetric encryption algorithm.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Next this data is split into N pieces using Rabin's IDA.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This IDA is configured with a threshold, in a manner similar to secret sharing schemes, but unlike secret sharing schemes the size of the resulting data grows by a factor of (number of fragments / threshold).
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For example, if the threshold were 10, and the number of IDA-produced fragments were 15, the total size of all the fragments would be (15/10) or 1.5 times the size of the original input.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In this case, this scheme is 10 times more efficient than if Shamir's scheme had been applied directly on the data.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The final step in secret sharing made short is to use Shamir secret sharing to produce shares of the randomly generated symmetric key (which is typically on the order of 16–32 bytes) and then give one share and one fragment to each shareholder.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A related approach, known as AONT-RS, applies an All-or-nothing transform to the data as a pre-processing step to an IDA.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The All-or-nothing transform guarantees that any number of shares less than the threshold is insufficient to decrypt the data.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] An information-theoretically secure *k*-of-*n* secret-sharing scheme generates *n* shares, each of size at least that of the secret itself, leading to the total required storage being at least *n*-fold larger than the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In multi-secret sharing designed by Matthew K.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Franklin and Moti Yung, multiple points of the polynomial host secrets; the method was found useful in numerous applications from coding to multi-party computations.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In space efficient secret sharing, devised by Abhishek Parakh and Subhash Kak, each share is roughly the size of the secret divided by *k* − 1.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This scheme makes use of repeated polynomial interpolation and has potential applications in secure information dispersal on the Web and in sensor networks.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This method is based on data partitioning involving the roots of a polynomial in finite field.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Some vulnerabilities of related *space efficient* secret sharing schemes were pointed out later.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] They show that a scheme based on interpolation method cannot be used to implement a (*k*, *n*) scheme when the *k* secrets to be distributed are inherently generated from a polynomial of degree less than *k* − 1, and the scheme does not work if all of the secrets to be shared are the same, etc.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A secret-sharing scheme can secure a secret over multiple servers and remain recoverable despite multiple server failures.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] The dealer may act as several distinct participants, distributing the shares among the participants.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This is one of the major concepts behind the Vanish computer project at the University of Washington, where a random key is used to encrypt data, and the key is distributed as a secret across several nodes in a P2P network.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] In order to decrypt the message, at least *t* nodes on the network must be accessible; the principle for this particular project being that the number of secret-sharing nodes on the network will decrease naturally over time, therefore causing the secret to eventually *vanish*.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] However, the network is vulnerable to a Sybil attack, thus making Vanish insecure.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Any shareholder who ever has enough information to decrypt the content at any point is able to take and store a copy of X.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Consequently, although tools and techniques such as Vanish can make data irrecoverable within their own system after a time, it is not possible to force the deletion of data once a malicious user has seen it.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] This is one of the leading conundrums of digital rights management.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] A dealer could send *t* shares, all of which are necessary to recover the original secret, to a single recipient.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] An attacker would have to intercept all *t* shares to recover the secret, a task which is more difficult than intercepting a single file, especially if the shares are sent using different media (e.g. some over the Internet, some mailed on CDs).
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] For large secrets, it may be more efficient to encrypt the secret and then distribute the key using secret sharing.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing is an important primitive in several protocols for secure multiparty computation.
[src:secrets-management/secret-sharing] Secret sharing can also be used for user authentication in a system.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets are being used everywhere nowadays, especially with the popularity of the DevOps movement.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Application Programming Interface (API) keys, database credentials, Identity and Access Management (IAM) permissions, Secure Shell (SSH) keys, certificates, etc.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Many organizations have them hardcoded within the source code in plaintext, littered throughout configuration files and configuration management tools.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There is a growing need for organizations to centralize the storage, provisioning, auditing, rotation and management of secrets to control access to secrets and prevent them from leaking and compromising the organization.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Often, services share the same secrets, which makes identifying the source of compromise or leak challenging.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This cheat sheet offers best practices and guidelines to help properly implement secrets management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The following sections address the main concepts relating to secrets management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Such a service could receive a considerable volume of requests within a large organization.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets used by your DevOps teams for your applications might be consumed differently than secrets stored by your marketeers or your SRE team.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You often find poorly maintained secrets where the needs of secret consumers or producers mismatch.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, you must standardize and centralize the secrets management solution with care.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Standardizing and centralizing can mean that you use multiple secret management solutions.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance: your cloud-native development teams choose to use the solution provided by the cloud provider, while your private cloud uses a third-party solution, and everybody has an account for a selected password manager.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By making sure that the teams standardize the interaction with these different solutions, they remain maintainable and usable in the event of an incident.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Even when a company centralizes its secrets management to just one solution, you will often have to secure the primary secret of that secrets management solution in a secondary secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance, you can use a cloud provider's facilities to store secrets, but that cloud provider's root/management credentials need to be stored somewhere else.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Standardization should include Secrets life cycle management, Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting of the secrets management solution, and life cycle management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note that it should be immediately apparent to an organization what a secret is used for and where to find it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The more Secrets management solutions you use, the more documentation you need.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When users can read and/or update the secret in a secret management system, it means that the secret can now leak through that user and the system they used to touch the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, engineers should not have access to all secrets in the secrets management system, and the Least Privilege principle should be applied.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret management system needs to provide the ability to configure fine-grained access controls on each object and component to accomplish the Least Privilege principle.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Manual maintenance not only increases the risk of leakage; it also introduces the risk of human errors while maintaining the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, it is better to limit or remove the human interaction with the actual secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Rotating certain keys, such as encryption keys, might trigger full or partial data re-encryption.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In a Kubernetes environment, a common pattern is to use a sidecar container that is responsible for retrieving secrets from a secrets manager and making them available to the main application container.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This decouples the application from the specifics of the secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Cloud-native secret managers often provide built-in support for automated rotation using serverless functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These examples demonstrate how you can create architectures that not only manage secrets securely but also automate the rotation process, significantly reducing the risk of compromised credentials.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] An additional level of security can be achieved by minimizing the time window where a secret is in memory and limiting the access to its memory space.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on your application's particular circumstances, this can be difficult to implement in a manner that ensures memory security.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Because of this potential implementation complexity, you are first encouraged to develop a threat model in order to clearly surface your implicit assumptions about both your application's deployment environment as well as understand the capabilities of your adversaries.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, it should be kept in mind while developing an appropriate threat model, that if an attacker already has access to the memory of the process handling the secret, by that time a security breach may have already occurred.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, it should be recognized that with the advent of attacks like Rowhammer, or Meltdown and Spectre, it is important to understand that the operating system alone is not sufficient to protect your process memory from these types of attacks.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This becomes especially important when your application is deployed to the cloud.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The only foolproof approach to protecting memory against these and similar attacks is to fully physically isolate your process memory from all other untrusted processes.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Despite the implementation difficulties, in highly sensitive environments, protecting secrets in memory can be a valuable additional layer of security.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, in scenarios where an advanced attacker can cause a system to crash and gain access to a memory dump, they may be able to extract secrets from it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, carefully safeguarding secrets in memory is recommended for untrusted environments or situations where tight security is of utmost importance.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, in lower-level languages like C/C++, it is relatively easy to protect secrets in memory.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, it may be worthwhile to implement this practice even if the risk of an attacker gaining access to the memory is low.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] On the other hand, for programming languages that rely on garbage collection, securing secrets in memory generally is much more difficult.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Remember, the goal is to minimize the time window where the secret is in plaintext in memory as much as possible.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For more detailed information, see Testing Memory for Sensitive Data from the OWASP MAS project.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Auditing is an essential part of secrets management due to the nature of the application.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You must implement auditing securely to be resilient against attempts to tamper with or delete the audit logs.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is essential that all auditing has correct timestamps.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, the secret management solution should have proper time sync protocols set up at its supporting infrastructure.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should monitor the stack on which the solution runs for possible clock-skew and manual time adjustments.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] New secrets must be securely generated and cryptographically robust enough for their purpose.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets must have the minimum privileges assigned to them to enable their required use/role.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should transmit credentials securely, such that ideally, you don't send the password along with the username when requesting user accounts.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead, you should send the password via a secure channel (e.g., mutually authenticated connection) or a side-channel such as push notification, SMS, email.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Refer to the Multi-Factor Authentication Cheat Sheet to learn about the pros and cons of each channel.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Applications may not benefit from having multiple communication channels, so you must provision credentials securely.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Open CRE project on secrets lookup for more technical recommendations on secret creation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should regularly rotate secrets so that any stolen credentials will only work for a short time.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Regular rotation will also reduce the tendency for users to fall back to bad habits such as reusing credentials.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on a secret's function and what it protects, the lifetime could be from minutes (think end-to-end encrypted chats with perfect forward secrecy) to years (consider hardware secrets).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] User credentials are excluded from regular rotation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These should only be rotated if there is suspicion or evidence that they have been compromised, according to NIST recommendations.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When secrets are no longer required or potentially compromised, you must securely revoke them to restrict access.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With (TLS) certificates, this also involves certificate revocation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should create secrets to expire after a defined time where possible.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This expiration can either be active expiration by the secret consuming system, or an expiration date set at the secrets management system forcing supporting processes to be triggered, resulting in a secret rotation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should apply policies through the secrets management solution to ensure credentials are only made available for a limited time appropriate for the type of credentials.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Applications should verify that the secret is still active before trusting it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In this day and age, there is no excuse given the ubiquitous adoption of TLS.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, you can effectively use secrets management solutions to provision TLS certificates.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consider the possibility that a secrets management service becomes unavailable for various reasons, such as scheduled downtime for maintenance.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It could be impossible to retrieve the credentials required to restore the service if you did not previously acquire them.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, choose maintenance windows carefully based on earlier metrics and audit logs.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, the backup and restore procedures of the system should be regularly tested and audited for their security.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A few requirements regarding backup & restore.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Lastly, you should implement emergency ("break-glass") processes to restore the service if the system becomes unavailable for reasons other than regular maintenance.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, emergency break-glass credentials should be regularly backed up securely in a secondary secrets management system and tested routinely to verify they work.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consistently enforce policies defining the minimum complexity requirements of passwords and approved encryption algorithms at an organization-wide level.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Using a centralized secrets management solution can help companies implement these policies.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, having an organization-wide secrets management policy can help enforce applying the best practices defined in this cheat sheet.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note: if you don't store metadata about the secret nor prepare to move, you will increase the probability of vendor lock-in.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] While not a direct replacement for all types of secrets (e.g., API keys, database credentials), passwordless authentication mechanisms like **OpenID Connect (OIDC)** can significantly reduce the attack surface by moving away from user-managed passwords.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead of passwords, applications rely on trusted identity providers (IdPs) to authenticate users and receive secure tokens.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Adopting passwordless authentication shifts the security focus from protecting static passwords to protecting dynamic tokens (e.g., ID tokens, access tokens, refresh tokens).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These tokens are bearer tokens, meaning anyone who possesses one can use them.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For more detailed guidance on securing OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect implementations, refer to the OAuth2 Cheat Sheet.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Building, testing and deploying changes generally requires access to many systems.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Deployment (CD) tools typically store secrets to provide configuration to the application or during deployment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, they interact heavily with the secrets management system.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Various best practices can help smooth out secret management in CI/CD; we will deal with some of them in this section.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling consumes (high-privilege) credentials regularly.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure that the pipeline cannot be easily hacked or misused by employees.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another alternative here is using the CI/CD pipeline to leverage the Encryption as a Service from the secrets management systems to do the encryption of a secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The CI/CD tooling can then commit the encrypted secret to git, which can be fetched by the consuming service on deployment and decrypted again.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note: not all secrets must be in the CI/CD pipeline to get to the actual deployment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead, make sure that the deployed services take care of part of their secrets management at their own lifecycle (e.g., deployment, runtime and destruction).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When secrets are part of your CI/CD tooling, it means that these secrets are exposed to your CI/CD jobs.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling can comprise, e.g., GitHub secrets, GitLab repository secrets, ENV Vars/Var Groups in Microsoft Azure DevOps, Kubernetes Secrets, etc.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Naturally, you can store secrets in a designated secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, you can use a solution offered by your (cloud) infrastructure provider, such as AWS Secrets Manager, Google Secrets Manager, or Azure Key Vault.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can find more information about these in section 4 of this cheat sheet.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another option is a dedicated secrets management system, such as Hashicorp Vault, Keeper, Conjur.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Here are a few do's and don'ts for the CI/CD interaction with these systems.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets do not necessarily need to be brought to a consumer of the secret by a CI/CD pipeline.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is even better when the consumer of the secret retrieves the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In that case, the CI/CD pipeline still needs to instruct the orchestrating system (e.g., Kubernetes) that it needs to schedule a specific service with a given service account with which the consumer can then retrieve the required secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The CI/CD tooling then still has credentials for the orchestrating platform but no longer has access to the secrets themselves.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The do's and don'ts regarding these credentials types are similar to those described in section 3.2.2.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling should have designated service accounts, which can only operate in the scope of the required secrets or orchestration of the consumers of a secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, a CI/CD pipeline run should be easily attributable to the one who has defined the job or triggered it to detect who has tried to exfiltrate secrets or manipulate them.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When you use certificate-based auth, the caller of the pipeline identity should be part of the certificate.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you use a token to authenticate towards the mentioned systems, make sure you set the principal requesting these actions (e.g., the user or the job creator).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Verify on a periodic basis whether this is (still) the case for your system so that you can do logging, attribution, and security alerting on suspicious actions effectively.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Attackers can use CI/CD tooling to extract secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] They could, for example, use administrative interfaces or job creation that exfiltrates the secret using encryption or double Base64 encoding.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, you should log every action in a CI/CD tool.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should define security alerting rules at every non-standard manipulation of the pipeline tool and its administrative interface to monitor secret usage.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Logs should be queryable for at least 90 days and stored for a more extended period in cold storage.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It might take security teams time to understand how attackers can exfiltrate or manipulate a secret using CI/CD tooling.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can leverage CI/CD tooling to rotate secrets or instruct other components to do the rotation of the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance, the CI/CD tool can request a secrets management system or another application to rotate the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, the CI/CD tool or another component could set up a dynamic secret: a secret required for a consumer to use for as long as it lives.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret is invalidated when the consumer no longer lives.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This procedure reduces possible leakage of a secret and allows for easy detection of misuse.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If an attacker uses a secret from anywhere other than the consumer's IP, you can easily detect it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can use pipeline tooling to generate secrets and either offer them directly to the service deployed by the tooling or provide the secret to a secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, the secret can be stored encrypted in git so that the secret and its metadata is as close to the developer's daily place of work as possible.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A git-stored secret does require that developers cannot decrypt the secrets themselves and that every consumer of a secret has its encrypted variant of the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance: the secret should then be different per DTAP environment and be encrypted with another key.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For each environment, only the designated consumer in that environment should be able to decrypt the specific secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A secret does not leak cross-environment and can still be easily stored next to the code.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consumers of a secret could now decrypt the secret using a sidecar, as described in section 5.2.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead of retrieving the secrets, the consumer would leverage the sidecar to decrypt the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When a pipeline creates a secret by itself, ensure that the scripts or binaries involved adhere to best practices for secret generation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Best practices include secure randomness, proper length of secret creation, etc. and that the secret is created based on well-defined metadata stored somewhere in git or somewhere else.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is best to use a designated secret management solution in any environment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Most cloud providers have at least one service that offers secret management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Of course, it's also possible to run a different secret management solution (e.g., HashiCorp Vault or Conjur) on compute resources within the cloud.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] We'll consider cloud provider service offerings in this section.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Sometimes it's possible to automatically rotate your secret, either via a service provided by your cloud provider or a (custom-built) function.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Generally, you should prefer the cloud provider's solution since the barrier of entry and risk of misconfiguration are lower.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you use a custom solution, ensure the function's role to do its rotation can only be assumed by said function.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For AWS, the recommended solution is AWS Secrets Manager.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Permissions are granted at the secret level.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Check out the Secrets Manager best practices.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With AWS Nitro Enclaves, you can create isolated compute environments to further protect and securely process highly sensitive data such as secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Enclaves are hardened, and restrict operator access, providing a trusted execution environment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A key feature is cryptographic attestation, which allows you to verify the enclave's identity and ensure only authorized code is running before provisioning secrets to it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This makes it a strong choice for scenarios requiring high assurance in secret handling.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For secrets being used in highly confidential applications, it may be needed to have more control over the encryption and storage of these keys.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] AWS offers CloudHSM, which lets you bring your own key (BYOK) for AWS services.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, you will have more control over keys' creation, lifecycle, and durability.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CloudHSM allows automatic scaling and backup of your data.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The cloud service provider, Amazon, will not have any access to the key material stored in **AWS CloudHSM**.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For GCP, the recommended service is Secret Manager.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Check out the Secret Manager best practices.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] GCP Confidential Computing is a technology that encrypts data in-use, while it is being processed.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This is achieved through services like **Confidential VMs** and **Confidential GKE Nodes**, which leverage AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization (SEV).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This ensures that even Google personnel cannot view the contents of the memory of your virtual machines, providing a high degree of protection for secrets that must be held in memory.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For Azure, the recommended service is Key Vault.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Contrary to other clouds, permissions are granted at the ***Key Vault*** level.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This means secrets for separate workloads and separate sensitivity levels should be in separated Key Vaults accordingly.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With Azure Confidential Computing, you can create trusted execution environments.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This technology isolates sensitive data within a protected container, ensuring that it is encrypted both at rest, in transit, and in use.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Services like **Azure Confidential Virtual Machines** and **Confidential Containers on ACI** utilize technologies like Intel SGX and AMD SEV-SNP to create these secure enclaves.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This prevents unauthorized access from cloud administrators, malware, or other tenants, making it a robust solution for secret management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For secrets being used in Azure environments and requiring special security considerations, Azure offers Azure Dedicated HSM.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This allows you more control over the secrets stored on it, including enhanced administrative and cryptographic control.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The cloud service provider, Microsoft, will not have any access to the key material stored in Azure Dedicated HSM.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you're using multiple cloud providers, you should consider using a cloud-agnostic secret management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This will allow you to use the same secret management solution across all your cloud providers (and possibly also on-premises).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another advantage is that this avoids vendor lock-in with a specific cloud provider, as the solution can be used on any cloud provider.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There are open-source and commercial solutions available.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This section will describe how a secret is encrypted and how you can manage the keys for that encryption in the cloud.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Server-side encryption of secrets ensures that the cloud provider takes care of the encryption of the secret in storage.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret is then safeguarded against compromise while at rest.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Encryption at rest often does not require additional work other than selecting the key to encrypt it with (See section 4.2.2).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] However, when you submit the secret to another service, it will no longer be encrypted.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is decrypted before sharing with the intended service or human user.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side encryption of secrets ensures that the secret remains encrypted until you actively decrypt it.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This means it is only decrypted when it arrives at the consumer.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You need to have a proper crypto system to cater for this.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Think about mechanisms such as PGP using a safe configuration and other more scalable and relatively easy to use systems.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side encryption can provide an end-to-end encryption of the secret: from producer to consumer.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When you encrypt a secret at rest, the question is: which key do you want to use?
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The less trust you have in the cloud provider, the more you will want to manage yourself.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Often, you can either encrypt a secret with a key managed at the secrets management service or use a key management solution from the cloud provider to encrypt the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The key offered through the key management solution of the cloud provider can be either managed by the cloud provider or by yourself.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Industry standards call the latter "bring your own key" (BYOK).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can either directly import or generate this key at the key management solution or using cloud HSM supported by the cloud provider.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can then either use your key or the customer main key from the provider to encrypt the data key of the secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The data key, in turn, encrypts the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By managing the CMK, you have control over the data key at the secrets management solution.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] While importing your own key material can generally be done with all providers (AWS, Azure, GCP), unless you know what you are doing and your threat model and policy require this, this is not a recommended solution due to its complexity and difficulty of use.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] IAM applies to both on-premises and cloud setups: to effectively manage secrets, you need to set up suitable access policies and roles.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Setting this up goes beyond policies regarding secrets; it should include hardening the full IAM setup, as it could otherwise allow for privilege escalation attacks.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure you never allow open "pass role" privileges or unrestricted IAM creation privileges, as these can use or create credentials that have access to the secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, make sure you tightly control what can impersonate a service account: are your machines' roles accessible by an attacker exploiting your server?
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Can service roles from the data-pipeline tooling access the secrets easily?
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure you include IAM for every cloud component in your threat model (e.g., ask yourself: how can you do elevation of privileges with this component?).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See this blog entry for multiple do's and don'ts with examples.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Leverage the temporality of the IAM principals effectively: e.g., ensure that only specific roles and service accounts that require it can access the secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Monitor these accounts so that you can tell who or what used them to access the secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, make sure that you scope access to your secrets: one should not be simply allowed to access all secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In GCP and AWS, you can create fine-grained access policies to ensure that a principal cannot access all secrets at once.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In Azure, having access to the key vault means having access to all secrets in that key vault.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is, thus, essential to have separate key vaults when working on Azure to segregate access.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Cloud services can generally provide a limited amount of API calls over a given period.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You could potentially (D)DoS yourself when you run into these limits.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Most of these limits apply per account, project, or subscription, so spread workloads to limit your blast radius accordingly.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, some services may support data key caching, preventing load on the key management service API (see, for example, AWS data key caching).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Some services can leverage built-in data key caching.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can enrich containers with secrets in multiple ways: build time (not recommended) and during orchestration/deployment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There are three ways to get secrets to an app inside a Docker container.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To inject secrets, you could create short-lived sidecar containers that fetch secrets from some remote endpoint and then store them on a shared volume mounted to the original container.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The original container can now use the secrets from the mounted volume.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The benefit of using this approach is that we don't need to integrate any third-party tool or code to get secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Once the sidecar has fetched the secrets, it terminates.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Examples of this include Vault Agent Sidecar Injector and Conjur Secrets Provider.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By mounting secrets to a volume shared with the pod, containers within the pod can consume secrets without being aware of the secrets manager.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should only expose secrets to communication mechanisms between the container and the deployment representation (e.g., a Kubernetes Pod).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Never expose secrets through external access mechanisms shared among deployments or orchestrators (e.g., a shared volume).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When the orchestrator stores secrets (e.g., Kubernetes Secrets), make sure that the storage backend of the orchestrator is encrypted and you manage the keys well.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Kubernetes Security Cheat Sheet for more information.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] In this section, we will discuss implementation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that it is always best to refer to the official documentation of the secrets management system of choice for the actual implementation as it will be more up to date than any secondary document such as this cheat sheet.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that these dynamic secrets often need to be created with the service we need to connect to.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] To create these types of dynamic secrets, we usually require long-term static secrets to create the dynamic secrets themselves.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets should never be retrievable by everyone and everything.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Continually monitor who/what, from which IP, and what methodology accesses the secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] For a secrets management solution to be effective, it must be easy for developers to adopt and use.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If the process is too complex, developers may resort to insecure practices.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] A focus on usability and a smooth onboarding experience is critical.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets Management goes hand in hand with encryption.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] After all, secrets must be stored encrypted somewhere to protect their confidentiality and integrity.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] You can use various encryption types to secure a secret as long as they provide sufficient security, including adequate resistance against quantum computing-based attacks.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Please note that in all cases, we need to preferably select an algorithm that provides encryption and confidentiality at the same time, such as AES-256 using GCM (Galois Counter Mode), or a mixture of ChaCha20 and Poly1305 according to the best practices in the field.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Convergent Encryption ensures that a given plaintext and its key results in the same ciphertext.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] This can help detect possible reuse of secrets, resulting in the same ciphertext.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The challenge with enabling convergent encryption is that it allows attackers to use the system to generate a set of cryptographic strings that might end up in the same secret, allowing the attacker to derive the plaintext secret.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Given the algorithm and key, you can mitigate this risk if the convergent crypto system you use has sufficient resource challenges during encryption.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Another factor that can help reduce the risk is ensuring that a secret is of adequate length, further hampering the possible guess-iteration time required.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] You should not store keys next to the secrets they encrypt, except if those keys are encrypted themselves (see envelope encryption).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Start by consulting the Key Management Cheat Sheet on where and how to store the encryption and possible HMAC keys.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] EaaS is a model in which users subscribe to a cloud-based encryption service without having to install encryption on their own systems.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] There are many approaches to secrets detection and some very useful open-source projects to help with this.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The Yelp Detect Secrets project is mature and has signature matching for around 20 secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] For more information on other tools to help you in the detection space, check out the Secrets Detection topic on GitHub.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Shift-left and DevSecOps principles apply to secrets detection as well.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] These general approaches below aim to consider secrets earlier and evolve the practice over time.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Many types of secrets exist, and you should consider signatures for each to ensure accurate detection for all.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] For more fun learning about secrets and practice rooting them out, check out the Wrong Secrets project.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets are like any other authorization token.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Create detection rules for each of the stages of the secret lifecycle.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Create documentation and update it regularly to inform the developer community on procedures and systems available at your organization and what types of secrets management you expect, how to test for secrets, and what to do in the event of detected secrets.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Quick response in the event of a secret exposure is perhaps one of the most critical considerations for secrets management.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Incident response in the event of secret exposure should ensure that everyone in the chain of custody is aware and understands how to respond.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] This includes application creators (every member of a development team), information security, and technology leadership.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] The primary goal of incident response is rapid response and containment.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Rotation: A new secret must be able to be quickly created and implemented, preferably via an automated process to ensure repeatability, low rate of implementation error, and least-privilege (not directly human-readable).
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Deletion: Secrets revoked/rotated must be removed from the exposed system immediately, including secrets discovered in code or logs.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets in code could have commit history for the exposure squashed to before the introduction of the secret, however, this may introduce other problems as it rewrites git history and will break any other links to a given commit.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If you decide to do this be aware of the consequences and plan accordingly.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets in logs must have a process for removing the secret while maintaining log integrity.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Consider using a standardized logging format and vocabulary such as the Logging Vocabulary Cheat Sheet to ensure that all necessary information is logged.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Managing secrets in a multi-cloud environment presents unique challenges due to the diversity of cloud providers and their respective services.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] This section discusses the challenges and best practices for managing secrets across multiple cloud providers.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Inconsistent Security Policies**: Different cloud providers may have varying security policies and practices, making it challenging to enforce consistent security standards across all environments.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Key Rotation**: Ensuring that keys are rotated consistently and securely across multiple cloud providers can be difficult, especially if each provider has different mechanisms for key rotation.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Access Control**: Managing access control for secrets across multiple cloud providers can be complex, as each provider may have different access control mechanisms and policies.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Auditing and Monitoring**: Ensuring comprehensive auditing and monitoring of secret access and usage across multiple cloud providers can be challenging due to the differences in logging and monitoring capabilities.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Standardize Security Policies**: Define and enforce standardized security policies for managing secrets across all cloud providers.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] This includes policies for key rotation, access control, and auditing.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Automate Key Rotation**: Implement automated key rotation processes to ensure that keys are rotated consistently and securely across all cloud providers.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Use tools and scripts to automate the rotation process and reduce the risk of human error.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Implement Fine-Grained Access Control**: Use fine-grained access control mechanisms to restrict access to secrets based on the principle of least privilege.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Ensure that access control policies are consistently enforced across all cloud providers.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] **Enable Comprehensive Auditing and Monitoring**: Implement comprehensive auditing and monitoring of secret access and usage across all cloud providers.
[src:secrets-management/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Use centralized logging and monitoring solutions to aggregate and analyze logs from multiple providers.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:secrets-management/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
